non_standard_settings_:
We need to get Microsoft SQL Server 2008 R2 Express or Standard Version installed on VM - ITSBEBEWSP02006 which is a WIndows 2008 R2 Enterprise server that has been set up to install Cisco Unified Attendant Console Advanced for Solna (Sweeden).
This is required as the MS SQL server is a required for the CUAC Advanced application to complete the Installation.

We already have a VM- ITSBEBEWSP02006 set up for the installation of CUAC Advanced server.

The CUAC Advanced application automatically installs the MSSQL express version if it doesn't find any SQL instance on the server. In this case, it tries to install the MSSQL instance, however, it then comes up with an error message saying that ' to install database on the server, a request needs to be raised in IRIS'.

When we did the same procedure the last time on a different VM, it successfully allowed the CUAC advanced set up to install the MSSQL express. This time, it is not letting us proceed and throws up an error as mentioned above.

The request RITM000013495452 that we raised was to get the SQL instance installed on the VM- ITSBEBEWSP02006. 

Please reach out to me for any additional details required or if there is any confusion on the requirements.

non_standard_settings_:
For seven users we have to move from the single PC to the multi user setup, with one front-end MS Terminal Server running the application interface (if you like the Excel macro ï)  and the back-end MS SQL server running the data base where the data used by the logic are stored.

The vendor request that the connection between the front end and the backend should be at LAN like speed, so I don't think that installing the client side on each PC remotely distributed would allow this. Moreover, putting the logic on one single point, will also simplify updgrades, sw. distributions and so on.
This is also the setup that they are proposing if you accept their offer to use the sw. as a service (option that was evaluated initially but excluded because we don't want to share data with them); in this case they don't use a Citrix frontend but a simple Windows terminal service.
For more information we can ask (Boretti, Alessandro [ITSIT] <aboretti@ITS.JNJ.COM>)
